## Bridge env files
##
## Next.js native env loading (we removed `dotenv-cli` in favor of it):
##
##   `bun dev`   reads `.env.development.local` → `.env.local` → `.env.development` → `.env`
##   `bun start` reads `.env.production.local`  → `.env.local` → `.env.production`  → `.env`
##
## Keys defined later in the chain are overridden by earlier ones, so
## per-mode files are the right place for things like a different
## `PORT` for dev vs prod. `.env.local` is your machine-only override
## (gitignored alongside the rest of `.env*`); use it for one-off
## tweaks you don't want shared.
##
## TL;DR — to run dev on 7777 and prod on a different port:
##
##     # .env.development
##     PORT=7777
##
##     # .env.production
##     PORT=7780
##
## You can ignore the per-mode files if both modes share the same
## values; just put everything in `.env`.

## Bridge dev server
PORT=7777
# BRIDGE_PORT overrides PORT for the bridge specifically (legacy /
# permission-hook precedent). If both are set, BRIDGE_PORT wins.
# BRIDGE_PORT=7777
# Comma-separated allow-list of dev-origin host(s) for cross-origin
# fetches during `bun dev`. Leave blank in single-host installs; only
# set this if you're running the bridge UI behind a reverse proxy
# while iterating locally and the dev server complains about origin.
ALLOWED_DEV_ORIGINS=
BRIDGE_DEMO_MODE=0

## Public-facing URLs
##
## BRIDGE_URL is what spawned children call back over (must stay
## loopback-reachable so child curl-self-register works). Override the
## default `http://localhost:<PORT>` only if you've rewired the bridge
## onto a non-default loopback (e.g. inside a sandbox / container).
# BRIDGE_URL=http://localhost:7777
##
## BRIDGE_PUBLIC_URL is the address you share with humans / Telegram —
## links and webhook payloads render this URL. Distinct from
## BRIDGE_URL because public traffic terminates TLS at your reverse
## proxy, but children still need loopback. Leave blank in localhost
## installs; the UI's `/settings` → "Public URL" field also writes
## this into `~/.claude/bridge.json#publicUrl`.
# BRIDGE_PUBLIC_URL=https://bridge.example.com
##
## NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL is read by the Next.js layout for OG / canonical
## tags. Optional; falls back to a sensible default.
# NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL=https://bridge.example.com

## Reverse-proxy trust
##
## Set to 1 ONLY when the bridge sits behind a reverse proxy you trust
## to set X-Forwarded-For / X-Real-IP correctly. With this off (the
## default), `getClientIp()` falls back to whatever Next.js exposes —
## the connecting IP, which is the safe choice on raw localhost.
# BRIDGE_TRUSTED_PROXY=0

## External binary discovery
##
## Override the path to the `claude` CLI. Defaults to whatever is on
## PATH; set this when you have multiple Claude Code installs and want
## the bridge to use a specific one (e.g. a beta build). Required when
## `which claude` returns nothing (Windows installs that didn't add the
## bin dir to PATH).
# CLAUDE_BIN=C:\Users\op\AppData\Roaming\npm\claude.cmd

## Stale-state reapers
##
## staleRunReaper sweeps the meta.json index for runs that look stuck.
## `running` rows are no longer time-cutoff'd — the OS process registry
## is the only signal: alive = trust it, gone = stale immediately.
## A coordinator orchestrating long retry chains can legitimately run
## for hours without being reaped.
##
##   - BRIDGE_QUEUED_STALE_MIN: a `queued` row gets flipped to `stale`
##     after N minutes never reaching `running` (queued is supposed to
##     last milliseconds — past the cutoff means the spawn never
##     promoted).
##   - BRIDGE_WORKTREE_STALE_HOURS: `.worktrees/<sid>/` directories
##     older than N hours (and not in any active session) are reaped.
# BRIDGE_QUEUED_STALE_MIN=2
# BRIDGE_WORKTREE_STALE_HOURS=24

## Verify-chain locking
##
## Set to 1 to serialize verify runs across sibling spawns of the
## same task — useful on machines where multiple verify scripts hit
## the same DB / port and step on each other. Defaults to off.
# BRIDGE_LOCK_VERIFY=0

## Bridge auth
##
## The web UI is gated behind an email + password the operator sets
## once. Two ways to set it the first time:
##
##   1. Open `http://localhost:7777/login` from the SAME machine —
##      the UI shows a setup form (loopback-only, refuses on LAN).
##   2. CLI fallback / rotation:
##
##          bun run set:password    (or: bun scripts/set-password.ts)
##
## Credentials live in `~/.claude/bridge.json#auth` — outside the repo
## so a `git pull` never touches them. There are no env vars to set;
## this section is here as a pointer.
##
## Pass `--rotate-secret` to the script after a suspected leak to
## re-roll the HMAC + internal-bypass tokens (invalidates all active
## sessions + every "trusted device" cookie).

## Skip composer permission popups
##
## By default the composer sends user-typed turns with `--permission-mode
## default`, so each tool call (Bash, Edit, …) hits the inline Allow/Deny
## popup. Coordinator + auto-spawned children already bypass; this flag
## adds a "Skip permissions" option to the mode dropdown that opts user
## turns into bypass too.
##
## Single-user localhost only. Setting it strips the XSS/CSRF guard on
## `POST /api/sessions/:id/message`, so don't enable on any deploy that
## proxies the bridge to the public internet.
# NEXT_PUBLIC_BRIDGE_ALLOW_BYPASS=1

## Telegram notifier
##
## Configured via the bridge UI at `/settings` now (writes to
## ~/.claude/bridge.json under the `telegram` key — same per-machine
## file the apps roster lives in). The env vars below are kept ONLY as
## a fallback for installs that haven't migrated yet; new operators
## should ignore them and use the UI panel instead.
##
##   1. Talk to @BotFather → /newbot, copy the token
##   2. Add the bot to your chat / group, then call
##      https://api.telegram.org/bot<TOKEN>/getUpdates and copy the
##      `chat.id` of the message you sent
##   3. Paste both into `/settings` → "Telegram notifier"
# TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=
# TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID=
